<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-314-910  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 314 910.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>IEEE Computer Graphics and Applications  March 1990 v10 n2 p24(9).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Volumetric rendering of computed tomography data: principles andtechniques. (technical)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Ney, Derek R.; Fishman, Elliot K.; Magid, Donna; Drebin, Robert A.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Three-dimensional imaging is intended to improve the interfacebetween the radiologist making a medical diagnosis and theclinician carrying out the treatment.andP;  Data from a transaxialcomputed tomography (CT) scan are usually displayed in atwo-dimensional planar format, which does not communicate thethree-dimensional nature of the area represented.andP;  Pixar, thecomputer graphics division of Lucas Films, has developed analgorithm for volumetric rendering, which is a technique thatallows three-dimensional images to be rendered of any volume dataset.andP;  The technique improves on other image generation methods bysupporting the use of a mixture paradigm for representation of thevolume to be rendered and using mathematical techniques to reduceor eliminate aliasing.andP;  Specific aspects of volumetric renderingare examined as they apply to medical CT data.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Three-Dimensional GraphicsTomographyMedical DiagnosisImaging TechnologyNew TechniqueAlgorithm AnalysisImage ProcessingVolumeResearch and Development.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Graph showing typical classification of one material. (chart)Graph showing how refractive indices are assigned from voxel CTnumbers. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>